[1
Date: Mon, 10 Jan 2000 13:13:24 -0600
From: Kang, Gagandeep <gkang@melnick.mvir.bcm.tmc.edu>

I read your posting on drug resistant typhoid fever in Bangalore, which was
interesting, but not surprising. In response to the moderator's comments on
disease confirmation and confirmation of resistance, most laboratories in
South India do the Widal test in addition to culture of blood and stool for
_S. typhi_. Ciprofloxacin resistance in _S. typhi_ in South India has been
reported and characterized in isolates obtained as early as 1994
Reference: Brown JC, Shanahan PM, Jesudason MV, Thomson CJ, Amyes SG, 1996.
Mutations responsible for reduced susceptibility to 4-quinolones in
clinical isolates of multi-resistant _Salmonella typhi_ in India. J.
Antimicrob. Chemother. 37(5):891-900.
--
Gagandeep Kang
Visiting Scientist,
Molecular Virology and Microbiology,
Baylor College of Medicine, Houston
and
Associate Professor of Microbiology,
Christian Medical College and Hospital,
Vellore, India
e-mail: gkang@melnick.mvir.bcm.tmc.edu
[Thanks for the useful insight and the reference to published data. I
would just comment that it was the article quoting an Indian physician that
suggested a problem with some hospitals doing the Widal test without
culture confirmation, not the moderator. - Mod.ES
